            <h3>&emsp;---dining etiquette</h3>
            <p>
                &emsp;&emsp;The Yi people pay attention to the distinction between men and women when dining, and the elders and the younger ones
                sit in the most honorable position. When entertaining guests, let the guests or elders eat the good wine and food first.
                At large banquets, male guests and female guests sit at two tables. When eating, everyone sits in a circle or a row,
                with a dustpan of rice, a wooden plate of meat and a wooden basin of soup and vegetables placed in the middle.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="shiwu">
            <h3>&emsp;---eating habits</h3>
            <p>
                &emsp;&emsp;The Yi people attach great importance to wine in their daily activities and social activities. Whether they are visiting
                relatives and friends, attending weddings, or visiting patients, they must bring wine with them. When a guest comes to
                your home, you should first pour him a glass of wine. Although the Yi people love to drink, they are not alcoholics.
                Drinking in circles is the most orthodox drinking culture of the Yi people: people sit in a circle on the ground, pass
                wine glasses to each other, and drink one after another. Ganggan wine is a specialty wine of the Yi people.
                The Yi people have complicated attitudes towards meat. As long as a person participates in or sees the process of
                slaughtering and hunting, the organizer of the slaughter or hunting will invite him to his home to eat meat that day.
                But eating too much meat will lead to ridicule because they think meat should be given to children.
                Yi people rarely cook vegetables. They like to boil vegetables or make them into pickled vegetables.
            </p>
        </div>
