        <div class="gongyi">
            <h2>Featured Craftsmanship</h2>
            <h3>&emsp;--lacquerware</h3>
            <p>
                Lacquer ware is mainly made of leather, wood, bamboo, and horn, and its shapes include basins, helmets, plates, etc. The
                decorative methods of lacquerware mainly include painting, carving, lacquer piling, and inlaying. Lacquer painting is
                the main method. The composition is mainly composed of three basic aspects: points, lines, and surfaces. When painting,
                the painter first uses a wide stroke to draw thick lines to divide the surface and outline the pattern, then uses a
                small wooden pen or brush to draw thin lines, add patterns and dots, and finally fill in the surface. Its decorative
                patterns mostly use animals and plants, production tools and the sun, moon and stars as patterns. The patterns are
                single pattern, two-sided continuous or four-sided continuous pattern, and the colors are mainly red, yellow and black.
            </p>
            <h3>&emsp;--silverware</h3>
            <p>
                The Yi silverware processing technology is very high and is widely used. The patterns of silverware are mostly based on
                animals, plants, sun, moon and stars. Among the Yi silverware, there are many drinking utensils and the most exquisite
                workmanship and shape. Among them, the Yi wine pots called "Moye" and "Sarebo" are unique. Their shapes are round or
                round, with a round or bird-shaped middle and a cylindrical or spire-shaped neck. When smoking, drink from the small
                tube on the side of the pot. The whole pot is completely closed except for a small hole at the bottom. The wine is
                poured from the bottom hole. Except for pouring the wine into the hole, it is usually placed upright.
            </p>
            <h3>&emsp;--Sculpture</h3>
            <p>
                There are mainly two types of carving: wood carving and stone carving. The woodcarving skills of the Yi people are
                mainly reflected in the eaves of houses, wooden cabinets, and interior siding. The patterns are mainly animals and
                plants. The technique includes both negative and positive carving. Stone carvings are mostly found on pillar stones,
                stone mortars, etc. There are many carvings of peacocks, eagles, tigers, suns, moons, etc., showing a strong sense of
                nature worship and totem worship.
            </p>
        </div>
