            <p>
                <strong>Date:</strong><br />&emsp;&emsp;The twenty-fourth day of the sixth lunar month.
                <br /><strong>Activities:</strong><br>&emsp;&emsp;Each village slaughters cattle and sheep and shares them collectively, prepares wine and meat to worship the ancestors,
                the elders light the sacred fire, and the high priest chants sutras and worships the fire. On the last night, everyone
                sang and danced around the bonfire.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="festival2">
            <img src="~/Content/Images/2/Festival1.jpg">
            <h2>Yi calendar Year</h2>
            <p>
                <strong>Date：</strong><br />&emsp;&emsp;One day from October 16th to October 30th in the lunar calendar.<br />
                <strong>Activities：</strong><br />
                &emsp;&emsp;Before the New Year, every household must chop three days' worth of firewood and prepare enough rice, noodles, salt and
                other food. On the morning before the Chinese New Year, every household has to clean their houses and courtyards. During
                the Chinese New Year, every household will kill a pig and use its internal organs to determine the owner's fortune for
                the coming year.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="festival3">
            <img src="~/Content/Images/2/Festival3.jpg">
            <h2>Painted Face Festival</h2>
            <p>
                <strong>Date：</strong><br />&emsp;&emsp;The first Snake Day in February of each year on the lunar calendar.<br />
                <strong>Origin：</strong><br />&emsp;&emsp;Ancient ancestors used pot ashes to smear their faces to drive away evil spirits.<br />
                <strong>Activities：</strong><br />&emsp;&emsp;During the festival, Bimo (priest of the Yi ethnic group) first leads the whole village in holding sacrificial
                activities. Young men and women wipe each other's faces with pot ashes. The darker the face is, the more good luck and
                happiness it will bring.
            </p>

        </div>
        <div class="festival4">
            <img src="~/Content/Images/2/Festival2.jpg">
            <h2>Tiger Festival</h2>
            <p>
                <strong>Date：</strong><br />&emsp;&emsp;Every year from the eighth to the fifteenth day of the first lunar month.<br />
                <strong>Origin：</strong><br />&emsp;&emsp;"Luo Luopu" is one of the many branches of the Yi people. In the Yi language, "Luo Luopu" means "tiger tribe" or "tiger
                people", so they believe that they are descendants of tigers and that tigers gave them It brings auspiciousness and
                happiness to life, so every year in the first month they follow the folk custom of Tiger Dance.<br />
                <strong>Activities：</strong><br />&emsp;&emsp;Do the tiger dance.
            </p>
        </div>
